Volume = {{8}},
Month = {{MAR 16}},
Abstract = {{The cross-pollination of most alpine plants depends on insects, whose
   altitudinal distribution is limited by temperature. However, although
   global warming is causing shifts in temporal and spatial species
   distribution, we are still largely unaware of how plant-pollinator
   interactions change with elevation and time along altitudinal gradients.
   This makes the detection of endangered interactions and species
   challenging. In this study, we aimed at providing such a reference, and
   tested if and how the major flower-visiting insect orders and families
   segregated by altitude, phenology and foraging preferences along an
   elevational gradient from 970 m to 2700 m in the Alps. Flies were the
   main potential pollinators from 1500 m, as bees and beetles decreased
   rapidly above that limit. Diptera, Coleoptera and Hymenoptera differed
   significantly in the angiosperm assemblages visited. Within Diptera, the
   predominant group, major families segregated by both phenology and
   foraging preferences along the gradient. Empidids, muscids and
   anthomyiids, whose role in pollination has never been investigated,
   dominated the upper part of the gradient. Our results thus suggest that
   flies and the peculiar plants they visit might be particularly at risk
   under global warming, and highlight the blatant lack of studies about
   critical components of these rich, yet fragile mountain ecosystems.}},
