Journal = {{PROCEEDINGS OF THE ROYAL SOCIETY B-BIOLOGICAL SCIENCES}},
Year = {{2018}},
Volume = {{285}},
Number = {{1872}},
Month = {{FEB 14}},
Abstract = {{Agricultural intensification is one of the main causes for the current
   biodiversity crisis. While reversing habitat loss on agricultural land
   is challenging, increasing the farmland configurational heterogeneity
   (higher field border density) and farmland compositional heterogeneity
   (higher crop diversity) has been proposed to counteract some habitat
   loss. Here, we tested whether increased farmland configurational and
   compositional heterogeneity promote wild pollinators and plant
   reproduction in 229 landscapes located in four major western European
   agricultural regions. High-field border density consistently increased
   wild bee abundance and seed set of radish (Raphanus sativus), probably
   through enhanced connectivity. In particular, we demonstrate the
   importance of crop-crop borders for pollinator movement as an additional
   experiment showed higher transfer of a pollen analogue along crop-crop
   borders than across fields or along semi-natural crop borders. By
   contrast, high crop diversity reduced bee abundance, probably due to an
   increase of crop types with particularly intensive management. This
   highlights the importance of crop identity when higher crop diversity is
   promoted. Our results show that small-scale agricultural systems can
   boost pollinators and plant reproduction. Agri-environmental policies
   should therefore aim to halt and reverse the current trend of increasing
   field sizes and to reduce the amount of crop types with particularly
   intensive management.}},
